 <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The initial optimal carbon price under hyperbolic discounting (8) is 
  <span class="italic">higher and rises at a faster rate</span> than the price under exponential discounting (7), since the discount rate falls with longer time horizons. The optimal carbon price (8) assumes commitment to an announced time path of future carbon prices. If the policy makers renege on predecessors’ plans and re-optimise at some future date, the carbon price is lowered again (due to the relatively high discount rate for short horizons) and rises monotonically as time progresses. In equilibrium, the carbon price is recalculated in each period and current policymakers take this into account when announcing their policies.
 </p>
